<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910307-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>910307-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Ames Department   Stores Noteholder   Sues Firm's Banker</HL><DATE>03/07/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   ADD</CO><IN>BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)SECURITIES (SCR)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   NEW YORK -- An Ames Department Stores Inc. noteholderfiled a lawsuit accusing the company's investment bankingfirm and former Ames executives of securities-law violations.   The lawsuit, which seeks class-action status, was filed infederal court in Manhattan and alleges that the investmentbanking firm, Wertheim Schroder andamp; Co., and the executivesengaged in a fraudulent scheme to artificially inflate theprice of Ames' senior subordinated notes. The $200 million innotes were issued May 16, 1989, to pay off debt stemming fromAmes' acquisition of Zayre Corp.</LP><TEXT>   The proposed class action seeks to include investors whobought the notes between May 16, 1989, and April 9, 1990, theday the company disclosed that it expected to post a loss of$228 million for the year ended Jan. 27, 1990.   Ames, a discount department store chain, wasn't named as adefendant because it currently is operating under protectionof Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code. A company can't besued while it is in bankruptcy proceedings.   The lawsuit, filed by noteholder Anthony Delano of Easton,Conn., alleges that the defendants made false and misleadingstatements about the company's financial condition andprospects, especially about its newly acquired Zayre stores.   Neither Wertheim Schroder officials nor officials of Ameswere available for comment.   Ames, based in Rocky Hill, Conn., filed for bankruptcy-lawprotection on April 25, 1990. Much of the company's problemshave stemmed from its Zayre stores.</TEXT></DOC>